# Web Theme And Tailwind

## Avoid AI-Slop Styling

- Do not add decorative rails, left borders, accent strips, blobs, glow stacks, glassmorphism, generic gradients, floating SaaS cards, or oversized blurred shadows as default visual interest.
- Decoration should earn its place by reinforcing the archival atlas concept, clarifying hierarchy, or communicating state. If it is only there to make an empty space feel designed, remove it.
- Prefer typography, spacing, page composition, subtle dividers, paper-toned surfaces, and restrained texture over ornamental flourishes.

## Visual Direction

- The visual direction is an archival atlas page: warm paper backgrounds, ink-like foreground text, muted botanical and map tones, and a sharper accent for active graph selections or primary actions.
- The palette should feel researched, local-first, and exploratory rather than SaaS-generic. Favor parchment, moss, mineral blue, ochre, and dark ink relationships over bright default Tailwind hues.
- In light mode, preserve the paper-and-ink feeling with warm surfaces and soft borders. In dark mode, keep the same archive mood with deep umber backgrounds, readable warm text, and accents that feel illuminated rather than neon.
- Use stronger color only to communicate state, selection, graph meaning, or action. Most surfaces should stay quiet so graph structure and word relationships carry the visual weight.
- Prefer atlas-page composition over stacked app cards: paint hero copy, graph headings, and primary page structure directly onto the background with divider rules and generous spacing.
- Use bordered surfaces only where containment helps interaction or scanning, such as search forms, popovers, node details, and small index/reference groups.
- Keep corners sharp and paper-like. Prefer `rounded-md` for contained page surfaces and about `6px` in component CSS. Reserve full pills for badges and compact controls only.
- Graph canvas backgrounds should read as map texture rather than decorative blobs. Use faint graticules, route/contour marks, grain, and vignettes; any map pattern inside the graph should pan and zoom with the graph viewport.
- Prefer borders, paper-toned surfaces, typography, spacing, and restrained texture for hierarchy. Small shadows are acceptable when they imitate paper separation, popovers, or selected graph marks; keep them close, low-contrast, and named through theme tokens such as `shadow-paper`, `shadow-panel`, or `shadow-overlay`.
- Do not scatter arbitrary `shadow-[...]` or heavy `drop-shadow(...)` values through components. Add a semantic shadow token in `apps/web/src/styles.css` when a new depth level is genuinely needed.
- Use Tailwind utilities for component layout, spacing, typography, borders, and interaction states in `apps/web`.
- Use semantic color utilities from `apps/web/src/styles.css` instead of raw palette classes. Prefer `bg-background`, `bg-surface`, `bg-surface-muted`, `bg-surface-raised`, `text-text`, `text-text-muted`, `border-border`, `border-border-strong`, `bg-accent`, `text-accent`, `bg-accent-soft`, and `text-danger`.
- Add new theme colors as CSS variables in `apps/web/src/styles.css`, expose them through `@theme inline`, then use the semantic utility in components. Do not scatter one-off values such as `bg-slate-900`, `text-emerald-600`, or arbitrary hex colors through Vue templates.
- Treat dark mode as first class. Any new surface, text, border, graph, or state color should work through the existing light/dark token values rather than through isolated `dark:` overrides.
- Use `dark:` variants for structural differences only when tokens cannot express the behavior cleanly.
- Keep graph-specific colors semantic. Prefer tokens such as `graph-node`, `graph-root`, `graph-edge`, `ancestor`, `descendant`, and `borrowed` for graph visualizations.
- The app has an explicit light/dark toggle that sets `light` or `dark` on the document root and uses system preference as the initial fallback. Preserve that behavior when touching theme code.

## Typography

- Treat typography as a small system, not a place for per-component invention. Use the existing `font-sans` serif stack for prose, headings, entry content, graph labels, and most page text.
- Use `font-label` only for interface chrome: buttons, form labels, navigation, tabs, badges, menu items, compact metadata labels, and uppercase section eyebrows.
- Keep primary page headings large, heavy, and tightly tracked. Use `font-black` with negative tracking for hero/page titles only; do not apply this display treatment to cards, buttons, body text, or dense metadata.
- Use uppercase, letter-spaced label text sparingly and consistently: `font-label`, `font-bold` or `font-black`, `uppercase`, and `tracking-[0.12em]` to `tracking-[0.16em]`. Do not invent nearby tracking values unless the surrounding component already establishes them.
- Body copy, explanations, empty states, and source text should stay readable and quiet: normal serif text, restrained size changes, and `text-text-muted` only for secondary information.
- Interactive text should use the shared label style rather than bespoke weights or decorative fonts. Prefer existing `Button`, `IconButton`, `TextField`, `Combobox`, `MenuItem`, and navigation patterns before adding new typography classes.
- Do not add one-off font families, arbitrary `font-[...]`, arbitrary line-height, decorative italics, mixed-case label experiments, or raw CSS `font-family` declarations in Vue components. Add a semantic font token in `apps/web/src/styles.css` only if a distinct recurring text role genuinely needs it.

## Voice

- Write UI copy in a clear, authoritative, straightforward, and unambiguous voice.
- Prefer short declarative sentences, concrete nouns, and active verbs. Tell the user what happened, what it means, and what to do next.
- Avoid hedging, filler, hype, cute phrasing, and vague labels. Do not say "maybe", "just", "magic", "supercharge", or "unlock" unless the product literally needs that meaning.
- Do not use em dashes in UI copy or documentation. Prefer a period, comma, colon, or a simpler sentence split.
- Keep implementation details out of user-facing copy. Do not mention imports, seed data, APIs, databases, edge types, metadata, or the data model unless the user is in an explicitly technical/admin context.
- Describe the user-visible result instead: a word page, source trail, lineage, entry, relationship, graph, search, path, or match.
- Preserve the archival atlas mood through precise language, not ornament. Favor words like `source`, `lineage`, `entry`, `relationship`, `search`, and `graph` when they match the feature.
- Button labels and errors should be direct: `Search`, `Reset`, `Close`, `No matches found`, `Import failed`, `Try another term`.

Example:

```vue
<main class="mx-auto grid max-w-6xl gap-8 px-6 py-8 text-text sm:gap-10 sm:py-12">
  <section class="border-b border-border-strong pb-8">
    <p class="font-label text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.12em] text-text-muted">Atlas section</p>
    <h1 class="text-5xl font-black tracking-[-0.06em]">Paint primary content on the page.</h1>
  </section>
  <section class="rounded-md border border-border bg-surface/75 p-5 shadow-paper">
    <p class="text-text-muted">Use contained surfaces for forms and reference slips.</p>
  </section>
</main>
```
